{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"732d811b-f9c2-4c30-a42f-1a5e73995328","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. Here's how:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\n# Install the tool if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `pe` (PrintException) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `setthread <id>` then `clrstack` | Inspect other threads |\n\n**Using LLDB (Linux) or WinDbg (Windows):**\n- **LLDB**: `lldb --core your-file.dmp` with the SOS plugin (`plugin load libsosplugin.so`)\n- **WinDbg**: Open the dump, load SOS via `.loadby sos coreclr`, then use `!clrstack`, `!pe`, etc.\n\n**Typical investigation flow:**\n1. Run `pe` to check if an unhandled exception caused the crash\n2. Run `clrthreads` to find faulting threads\n3. Run `clrstack` on the faulting thread to get the call stack\n4. Use `dso` (dump stack objects) to inspect local variables\n\nWould you like me to walk you through any of these steps on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"78691b16-61f7-451d-b4fb-fea9a743c54d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description says it's for collecting/configuring crash dumps, NOT for analyzing them. It explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo I should NOT invoke the dump-collect skill. Instead, I'll provide guidance directly.","outputTokens":488,"requestId":"D7C4:11233D:FF6269:1258783:69F2B6AC"},"id":"2edd4af5-2ce5-4a85-9613-43c88516132b","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:56:08.57